item.description:
Quick checklist to cover most use cases.
1. Use named element tags instead of &lt;div&gt;. These tags are more descriptive than &lt;div&gt;.
&lt;header&gt; &lt;nav&gt;
&lt;main&gt; &lt;section&gt; &lt;article&gt; &lt;aside&gt; &lt;blockquote&gt;
&lt;form&gt; &lt;fieldset&gt;
&lt;figure&gt; &lt;figcaption&gt;
&lt;footer&gt;
For an in-depth guide, please refer to this article on the semantic meaning of each tag.
1a. Forms and Inputs If the element functions as a button, use &lt;button&gt; (as opposed to just &lt;a&gt; or &lt;div&gt;). Buttons have inbuilt keyboard controls for focusing, selecting and clicking.
